            "body": "I recommend creating a mapping for this kind of thing. For example, to opt-in to \"find all files\" without messing with 'path', I use:\n\n    :nnoremap <C-f> :edit **/\n\nMappings are a 100% valid part of the \"options\" interface of Vim. Something might not be a formal \"option\", but mappings exist to serve the infinite universe of other use-cases.\n\nThere is also a tracking issue somewhere to enhance cmdline aliases, so that you could alias lowercase `:e` and it'll do whatever you want. \n\nMeanwhile, `nvim_parse_cmd()` is very useful for intelligently parsing the cmdline, so you can create a robust mapping.\n\nAlternatively, you could request your idea at https://github.com/vim/vim and we'll merge whatever they do, probably.\n\n> Add a `wildshowdotfiles` option to customize this behavior. It could either be a simple boolean,\n\nNot another boolean please ðŸ˜­ \n\n\n> 'allowlist' syntax like `!.*` could be added to `wildignore` to indicate that those paths should always be shown.\n\nThat could be interesting, I think there's precedent in other options.",
